\\subsubsection*\{Column B: $j$-Invariant\}\
The $j$-invariant $j(E) \\in \\mathbb\{Q\}$ is an isomorphism invariant of the\
curve: two elliptic curves over $\\overline\{\\mathbb\{Q\}\}$ are isomorphic if and\
only if they have the same $j$-invariant. It is a rational number computed from\
the coefficients $[a_1, a_2, a_3, a_4, a_6]$ of the minimal Weierstrass model\
(column~B of Table~8) via the auxiliary quantities\
\\begin\{align*\}\
  b_2 &= a_1^2 + 4a_2, \\\\\
  b_4 &= a_1 a_3 + 2a_4, \\\\\
  b_6 &= a_3^2 + 4a_6, \\\\\
  b_8 &= a_1^2 a_6 - a_1 a_3 a_4 + 4a_2 a_6 + a_2 a_3^2 - a_4^2,\
\\end\{align*\}\
then\
\\[\
  c_4 = b_2^2 - 24b_4, \\qquad\
  D = -b_2^2 b_8 - 8b_4^3 - 27b_6^2 + 9b_2 b_4 b_6,\
\\]\
and finally\
\\[\
  j(E) = c_4^3/D.\
\\]\
Values are shown in factored form (e.g.\\ $-2^\{12\}$ for 11a1, $0$ for the CM\
curve 27a1, $1728$ for 32a1).\
\
