\\subsubsection*\{Column C: Generator Canonical Heights\}\
N\\'\{e\}ron-Tate height $\\hat\{h\}(P)$. For each generator $P \\in E(\\mathbb\{Q\})$, the canonical (N\\'\{e\}ron-Tate) height $\\hat\{h\}(P)$ is a positive definite quadratic form on $E(\\mathbb\{Q\})/E(\\mathbb\{Q\})_\{\\text\{tors\}\}$:\
$$\\hat\{h\}: E(\\mathbb\{Q\}) \\to \\mathbb\{R\}_\{\\geq 0\}$$\
satisfying $\\hat\{h\}([n]P) = n^2 \\hat\{h\}(P)$ and $\\hat\{h\}(P) = 0 \\iff P \\in E(\\mathbb\{Q\})_\{\\text\{tors\}\}$.\\footnote\{`` $[s]P$ '' means multiplication of $P$ by the scalar $s$.\} In our table, no group $E(\\mathbb\{Q\})$ has more than one generator, so we report at most one height per curve.\
Code:\
\\begin\{lstlisting\}\
def generator_heights_string(E):\
    try:\
        gens = E.gens()\
        if len(gens) == 0:\
            return "none"\
        heights = [float(g.height()) for g in gens]  # CORRECTED\
        return "|".join([f"\{h:.4f\}" for h in heights])\
    except Exception as ex:\
        return f"error: \{ex\}"\
# Lines 111-119\
\\end\{lstlisting\}\
\
References: Canonical height theory: \\cite[Chapter VIII]\{silverman:aec\}. Computational methods: \\cite\{cremona:algorithms, silverman:computing\}.\
\
\\subsubsection*\{Column D: Regulator\}\
The regulator $\\text\{Reg\}(E/\\mathbb\{Q\})$ is the determinant of the height pairing matrix. For generators $P_1, \\ldots, P_r$ of $E(\\mathbb\{Q\})/E(\\mathbb\{Q\})_\{\\text\{tors\}\} \\cong \\mathbb\{Z\}^r$, define the $r \\times r$ matrix\
$$H_\{ij\} = \\langle P_i, P_j \\rangle = \\hat\{h\}(P_i + P_j) - \\hat\{h\}(P_i) - \\hat\{h\}(P_j)$$\
Then $\\text\{Reg\}(E/\\mathbb\{Q\}) = |\\det(H)|$. By convention, $\\text\{Reg\} = 1$ for rank 0.\
\
